Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Sandford, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sanford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Sandford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sandford","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in England with names derived from Old English <i>sand</i> ‘sand’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford, river crossing’, such as Sandford in Warcop (Westmorland), Sandford in Sonning and Dry Sandford in Abingdon (both Berkshire), Sandford on Thames and Sandford Saint Martin (both Oxfordshire), Great and Little Sampford (Essex), Sandford Orcas (Dorset), Sandford, Sampford Courtney, Sampford Peverell, and Sampford Spiney (all Devon), Sampford Arundel and Sampford Brett (both Somerset), and Sandford (Shropshire). See also   Sandiford  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Sanford was born in 1340, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Richard de Sandford II, was 39 and his mother, Isabel, was 31. He married Alice Boteler about 1369. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1386, at the age of 46, his occupation is listed as high sheriff of shropshire in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. He died on 13 April 1426, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1340–13 April 1426":"1340–13. aprill 1426","1340–1426":"1340–1426","1342–1403":"1342–1403","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1340–1381":"1340–1381","1370–1451":"1370–1451","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1301–1348":"1301–1348","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","13 April 1426":"13. aprill 1426","1374":"1374","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","ABT 1369":"umbes 1369","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1381":"1381","1426":"1426","1348":"1348","1403":"1403","1346":"1346","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1301":"1301","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1386":"1386","1342":"1342","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1372":"umbes 1372","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Sandford, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire,